Workout:

- 15:00 easy Endurance Run warm up
- 6-8 x 00:15 fast strides / 1:30 jog recovery
- 10:00 cooldown at an easy ER effort

Run the stride intervals at a fast but relaxed and controlled effort. Strides are not sprints and you shouldn't be straining. Gently accelerate for the first 5s, hold top speed for 5s and decelerate for 5s.

Warm up thoroughly prior and begin workout at an easy effort. Find a hill with a 4-8% grade and run fast up whilst remaining relaxed and controlled. Recover by walking back to your starting point and don't start another rep until fully rested or 90s is up.

Hill strides improve mechanical power output, lower leg strength, running economy and reinforce good running form.

Workout type: Run
This is an all-out effort for 3000m (1.86 miles). Aim is to complete the distance in the quickest time possible. The aim is to measure your aerobic fitness, find out whether your fitness is improving and calculate your current training paces for different distances.

The effort/intensity should be hard but sustainable for the whole distance. Be sure to choose a flat, fast road or track to perform the test on. Do not choose a day when there is a tailwind or a downhill course.

Perform a thorough warm up (10-15mins) before starting the test. This can include dynamic stretching, drills and strides.

After be sure to hydrate, eat well and get a good nights sleep!

Workout type: Run
The 30min Time Trial Method

Find somewhere which is conducive to fast running i.e. treadmill, track or flat road.
Ensure you are able to measure time, distance and heart rate. Pick a day you are not feeling fatigued.

Ensure a proper warm up before the test.

Run at the fastest pace you can sustain for 30mins. Try not to start too fast and have to slow down due to fatigue as this will produce an inaccurate result.

At the 10 minute mark, make a note of your heart rate. When you stop at 30 minutes, make a note of your heart rate. Add these two heart rate values together then divide by two and this is your Lactate Threshold Heart Rate. The average pace for the entire 30min TT is your Lactate Threshold Pace, assuming your pace was fairly steady.

These values are usually fairly accurate but will never be as accurate as laboratory testing.
Planned Time: 0:30
